TY  - JOUR
T1  - Uncertainty and Technical Communication Patterns
AU  - Brown, James W.
AU  - Utterback, James M.
Y1  - 1985/03/01
PY  - 1985
DA  - 1985/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.31.3.301
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.31.3.301
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 301
EP  - 311
VL  - 31
IS  - 3
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper examines the relationship between research and development peoples' perceptions of uncertainty in their firm's competitive environment and their patterns of technical communication. Measures of both these attributes of six R&D groups, two in each of three industries, are reported and analyzed here. Technical people who saw the world (competitors, suppliers, customers, technology and regulations) outside their firm as more uncertain also were found to seek greater contact with sources of information outside their firms. The gatekeeper phenomenon was found to be more pronounced, but less formal and less well defined in these firms. Gatekeepers in general were found to perceive a higher level of uncertainty than others in all six firms.
AB  - This paper examines the relationship between research and development peoples' perceptions of uncertainty in their firm's competitive environment and their patterns of technical communication. Measures of both these attributes of six R&D groups, two in each of three industries, are reported and analyzed here. Technical people who saw the world (competitors, suppliers, customers, technology and regulations) outside their firm as more uncertain also were found to seek greater contact with sources of information outside their firms. The gatekeeper phenomenon was found to be more pronounced, but less formal and less well defined in these firms. Gatekeepers in general were found to perceive a higher level of uncertainty than others in all six firms.
